# API Design

## Epics
- GET /api/epics
- POST /api/epics
- GET /api/epics/{id}
- PUT /api/epics/{id}
- DELETE /api/epics/{id}

---

## Features
- GET /api/epics/{epic}/features
- POST /api/features
- PUT /api/features/{id}
- DELETE /api/features/{id}

---

## Tasks
- GET /api/features/{feature}/tasks
- POST /api/tasks
- GET /api/tasks/{id}
- PUT /api/tasks/{id}
- DELETE /api/tasks/{id}

### Task actions
- PATCH /api/tasks/{id}/status
- PATCH /api/tasks/{id}/assign
- PATCH /api/tasks/{id}/priority
- PATCH /api/tasks/{id}/order

---

## Task History
- GET /api/tasks/{id}/history

---

# AI Capabilities

AI agents (via API tokens with `is_ai = true`) can:
- Create tasks
- Update tasks
- Change status
- Assign tasks
- Modify priority

AI agents cannot:
- Bypass audit logging
- Access unauthorized resources
- Delete history records

---

# Data Rules

- Tasks must belong to a Feature
- Features must belong to an Epic
- No subtasks allowed
- All changes are audited

---

# Ordering

- `order_index` controls manual ordering within a Feature

---

# Response Format (important for AI + UI)

All task responses MUST include:

```json
{
  "id": 1,
  "title": "Fix webhook handler",
  "status": "doing",
  "last_change": {
    "actor_type": "ai",
    "label": "AI"
  },
  "last_change_at": "2026-04-22T10:00:00Z"
}



## UI Requirements

### Visual distinction of changes

#### AI changes
- Color: blue/purple indicator  
- Label: "AI updated"

#### User changes
- Color: green/neutral indicator  
- Label: "User updated"

---

### History view

Each task must display:

- chronological history  
- actor type per entry (AI/User)  
- old vs new values  
- timestamp per change  

---

## System Rules

- No subtasks (only Tasks under Features)  
- All mutations must be logged  
- AI is a first-class actor type  
- No AI provider names stored or exposed  
- API-first architecture  